<br>
The Treaty of Maastricht, signed several years ago, increased the power of the European Union to encompass a uniform diplomatic representation platform, but on the whole, it is important to make certain distinctions.<br>
<br>
1. Is the European Union a country? No. <br>
<br>
2. Is the European Union a sovereign entity? No.<br>
<br>
3. Is the European Union a confederation? Perhaps some day, but presently, participation in the European Union is purely voluntary (much to the ire of the French and the Germans, who want to see a &quot;United States of Europe&quot;), and even the states who are most committed to it have no desire to participate in it if it becomes truly confederate or has federal ambitions.<br>
<br>
4. Will the European Union ever become a Federal State? This is highly unlikely, given that most countries (though, admittedly, not all) in the history of civilization have shared a common culture, language and tradition -- and the Europeans share none of these, save for a common cultural history, which following World War II, has given them the impetus to provide for mutual economic planning in an effort to reconstruct their lands (and later, to compete with the United States - who accounts for over 40% of the world's economy; and Japan, who accounts for some 11% of the world economic output). <br>
<br>
Unfortunately, the more that the European Union expands Eastward, it will suffer the economic burden of the states that it includes in the Euro Compact. Consider this fact: Spain has a GDP of 500 billion Euros. The <!--EZCODE BOLD START--><strong>combined</strong><!--EZCODE BOLD END--> GDP of all Eastern European Nations, and former states of the Soviet Union, except Russia, is less than 400 billion Euros. (Source: The World Bank, 2002 NDP Report.)<br>
<br>
My personal predictions are that several generations of institutionalization will enable a European Federal System to emerge, but long after any of us are around to see it. There are 500 million citizens in what is considered non-Russian Europe, and though they lack the natural resources to establish themselves as a major agrarian or industrial power, their talents, their resolve, their ingenuity and their energy more than make them a formidable people and a powerful ally.<br>
<br>
That being said, I think even a European Union is unlikely to constitute a significant political or military threat to the global dominance of the United States. I infer the only other historical analogy available to us - the overwhelming might of Rome, challenged by the waning power of a re-unifying Persia. It's comparing two distinctly different notions. Economically, however, I think we'll be in for an interesting time.<br>
<br>
